Question Two

Conclusion

I see that more males are getting accepted into college. The number is about double the females. Moving to the next plot, looking at each department, it is almost male-dominated again. In some departments, the number of females outweighs the males but the males are not so far behind.

I would say yes that the higher paying job you have the more stress that you will have. The correlation between them is not a very strong one. Just by estimating, I would say it is positively correlated between 6.and .7. Call center

Question one

busycalls = rep(200, 6)
regcalls = rep(60, 6)
nsim = 1e5
lambda = 5*sum(busycalls)
week_of_busy_calls = rpois(nsim, lambda = lambda)

Expected number of calls

mean(week_of_busy_calls)
## [1] 6000.193

Question two

200/30
## [1] 6.666667

they should have about 7 operators per hour to handle the busy days

Question three

Took the weighted average to factor in the the probability of it being a busy day or regualar day

ll = (.8*sum(regcalls) + .2*sum(busycalls))

Simualtion

sim = rpois(nsim, lambda = ll)

Average number of calls they get in a day

mean(sim)
## [1] 528.0462

Question Four

If you are during it on the number of operators, you need per hour and they work right though the day you would need about 4 operators per hour. I say this because when I simulated the weighted average of number of calls during the day you get a mean of 528 and the highest value of simulated trials amounted to around 600 calls per day. So, then I took 600 and divided it by 6 because of it being a six-hour work day. That gave about 100 calls per hour and then I divided that number by 30 to get how many operators you would need in that given hour. I would pick the weighted average because if you choose either the busy or regular day you might have idle capacity or your workers are fully utilized and still not meeting the demand of the calls.
